observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following-
a. create an inventory team to conduct a complete physical inventory of all assets owned by the Municipality, as well as disposal committee to dispose of all unserviceable property;
b. maintain and update property tags and stock/property cards by the Property Custodian;
c. accomplish (ARE/PARE) for equipment issued to end-user and renew the same every three years thereafter or upon the transfer of issued equipment to another end-user;
d. exert more efforts to secure the documents of properties not provided with depreciation;
e. identify unserviceable properties and record the same in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property to facilitate the disposal and eventual dropping from the books; and
f. transfer all completed projects to General Fund and subject the same to depreciation.

a. the head of agency and other responsible officials, in respect of their fiscal responsibility, are enjoined to-
a.1) conduct an immediate investigation and appropriate action on the cause of the cash in bank deficiency which is indicative of misappropriation of funds; and
a.2) take immediate action to fairly present the balance of Trust Liability-DRRM account and Cash in Bank (CIB) for MDRRM;
b. concerned officials undergo training/seminar to the overall management, monitoring and utilization of the LDRRM fund;
c. address the causes of non- reconciliation of the balances at year-end; and
d. responsible officials implementing the LDRRMF projects strictly adhere to the provisions of the COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
 Update the Report of Collections and Deposits submitted by the collector on a daily basis;
 Reflect the actual date of remittance of the collection in the cashbooks of the Municipal Treasurer; 
 Reflect the actual date of checks issued for cash advances and the actual date of liquidation of the cash advances in the cashbook;
 Indicate the series of accountable forms or the RCD number in the cashbook; and
 At least once per quarter, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of their books and to reflect all reconciling items in both books affected to support the assertion of the Municipality on the balances of the Cash in Bank, Cash Local Treasury and Payroll accounts as presented in the Financial Statement.

Therefore, recommended the following:
 Review the manner of purchases of supplies once purchased;
 Provide bodega for the delivered inventories for storage prior to distribution/withdrawal to the requesting department/office;
 Employ the Perpetual Inventory Method, if there are no budgetary constraints. Once provided, maintain the SLC and the stock cards upon delivery of purchased inventories and use the Moving Average Method for costing inventories in conformity with existing regulations.

Therefore, in view of the above observations/gaps noted, we reiterated our recommendation as last year’s:

 • On comprehensive conduct of physical count:
    - Conduct an immediate and thorough physical count of PPE by designating personnel, who is not handling cash transactions, to do the activity.
    - Follow the RPCPPE format as provided in Annex 49, Volume II, LGU-NGAS Manual; Provide property numbers on physically counted assets for identity of the properties;
    - Issue ARE on all properties counted, which were in the hands of accountable officers.
    - Retrieve all necessary documents in the transfer of completed projects under SEF or Trust Fund and transfer the same to the General Fund books. Subject the transferred property to depreciation;
    - Maintain and update the PPELC as well as the different property ledgers;
    - Maintain and update property cards by the Property Custodian;
    - Reconcile the PPELC, property cards and the physically counted properties;
    - If budget permits, create a General Services Office (GSO) manned by a permanent personnel who will handle the Municipality’s properties other than the Municipal Treasurer as the property custodian.

 • On properties not provided with depreciation
    - Exert all efforts to secure the documents of properties not provided with depreciation; and/or
    - Appraise all properties not provided with depreciation and make a sound decision on the amounts of impairments to present fairly the balances of the PPE and then provide depreciation;

 • On trust fund properties
    - Exert effort to locate documents related to the booked-up properties under Trust Fund;
    - Secure documents related to the PPEs recorded in the Trust Fund books, if none can be retrieved from the file of the Municipality, by communicating with the funding agency; and
    - Transfer all completed projects’ properties to General Fund and subject the same to depreciation.
